A total of 321 corpora were initially considered. We excluded 10 because at least some of the children were not typically developing; 11 because they were diary studies; 21 because data was collected in the lab or school; 8 because data was not available; 19 because only the child or the adult were transcribed; 65 because speech was triggered by a task (elicitation, story-telling, etc.); 3 because the conversation involved exclusively unfamiliar adults.

After these exclusions, 147 remained. The following analyses will continue only on these included corpora.

## [1] "Sweden & Portugal"

We had WDI information for 232 countries, of which 46 were present in CHILDES. GDP data was available for 190 countries overall, and 46 countries in CHILDES. Education information was available for 73 countries overall, and 31 countries in CHILDES. Information on the proportion of the population that was urban was available for 213 countries overall, and 46 countries in CHILDES.

Fertility rate was obtained from Our World in Data, which had 202 countries overall for the selected year, and 43 of them were represented in CHILDES.

At the level of the population

The samples are varied in geographic terms, with corpora for every peopled continent. Specifically, 3 corpora were collected in Africa; 30 in Asia; 65 in Western Europe, and a further 31 in Non-Western Europe; 12 in North America and 65 in Latin America. Only 1 was collected in Oceania.

The samples, however, over-represent richer countries, with relatively educated populations, living mostly in urban settings, and having relatively small families (Figure XX).

At the level of the family

A total of 65 different languages or language combinations (for bilingual and multilingual children) were reportedly spoken in the corpora. The precise list is (multiple languages spoken within the family are separated by /, & indicates two participant subsamples in terms of languages spoken): Afrikaans, Arabic, Basque, Brazilian Portuguese, British English, Cantonese, Catalan, Catalan/Spanish, Cree, Croatian, Czech, Danish, Dutch, Dutch/French & Dutch/Italian, English, English/Cantonese, English/Dutch, English/French, English/Hebrew, English/Japanese, English/Mandarin, English/Mandarin/Cantonese, English/Russian, English/Spanish, Estonian, European Portuguese, Farsi, French, French/Russian, German, German/Spanish, Greek, Hebrew, Hungarian, Hungarian/Catalan/Spanish, Hungarian/Farsi/English, Icelandic, Indonesian, Irish, Italian, Italian/German, Jamaican, Japanese, Korean, Kuwaiti Arabic, Mandarin, Norwegian, Nungon, Polish, Portuguese/Swedish/English, Romanian, Russian, Serbian, Sesotho, Slovenian, Spanish, Spanish & Spanish/English, Spanish/Catalan, Spanish/Galician, Swedish, Taiwanese, Tamil, Thai, Turkish, Welsh.

Educated

We then investigated the extent to which samples themselves captured families with diverse educational backgrounds. There were 77 missing values (52%); and NA were described as diverse, without clarifying the range of education covered. Of the remaining 67 samples, 3 had at least some parents with primary-level education; 9 had parents with secondary school education as the lower bound, and a further 3 had some college as the lower bound. Thus, the majority of the samples (N = 52, 78%) portrayed children whose parents had a graduate or a post-graduate degree.

Urban versus rural

Samples were also very homogeneous in terms of the type of community represented: 46 (90% of the samples for which this variable was not missing) were described as industrialized or urban, and one additional one as both rural and urban. Only 5 samples were described as farming or rural.

Household structure

As for household structure, there was a great deal of missing data, with only 59 (40%) of the samples specified. Among these, 51 (86%) were nuclear; in 7 (12%) were extended; and in one sample structure varied.

Siblings

It was not the case that the majority of children were single children. In fact, only 20 samples (24% of samples having information on siblings) were constituted exclusively by children with no siblings, and the remaining had at least some siblings. However, it should be born in mind that this variable was missing for 62 samples (42% of included samples).

Confounds

Above, we suggested that our samples are biased in several ways but perhaps it is hard to separate these biases. That is, some readers may have the intuition that Western, Educated, Industrialized, Rich, and Infertile are correlated in the world, and thus it will be hard to fix one without fixing the others and vice versa. One way to address this concern which has been suggested in other work is to study within-country variation. But we also want to know are these aspects confounded in terms of between-country variation?
